CRASH SUMMARY: On 10/8/2023 at approximately 2152 hours, Forestville Barrack troopers were dispatched to the area of southbound Crain Highway south of Route 50 (Bowie) for a two-vehicle collision involving a passenger vehicle and a dump truck. The operator of the passenger vehicle was declared deceased by EMS, so the Forestville Barrack Duty Officer requested the CVED respond to complete a post-crash investigation report. The crash team was notified of the incident and advised that a barrack re-constructionist could handle the DCIR so TFC Jacob Muller of the Waterloo barrack responded to conduct the collision reconstruction. Sgt. Hentnick, of the Upper Marlboro Weight and Inspection Facility, called me, ST Duane Rust #6313, at 2302 hours and requested that I respond to the scene to complete the PCIR. I arrived at the scene at 0002 hours on 10/9/2023. Upon arrival, I observed a white and black dump truck overturned onto its passenger side. Its load of asphalt had spilled onto the right shoulder off of the roadway. The motor carrier was DD Truckings Fort Washington LLC of Ft. Washington, Maryland (USDOT# 3650881). Tire skid marks were observed for approximately 150 feet leading from lane 2 to the area of the overturn. The white Honda Civic had come to a final rest off of the right side of the roadway behind the area where the dump truck was. The Honda had rotated nearly 180 degrees and was facing opposite the direction of travel. The debris field stretched the length of the skid marks. The operator of the dump truck, Santos Rodriguez Bermudez, had been transported to the hospital prior to my arrival. TFC Muller provided me with his drivers license, which was a Class-C non-CDL license. The force of the collision caused 3 of the 4 tires on axle 4 to blow out and become unseated from the rims. The axle 4 brake chamber was completely destroyed. Emergency and service side air hoses were sheared off at the distribution block on axle 4. The axle 4 left axle housing was broken causing the axle to be shifted out of its normal position. Silverline Towing responded to upright and remove the dump truck from the scene. margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; margin-top:0in; text-align:center"> margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; margin-top:0in; text-align:left"> B. Detailed Crash Investigation Report (For review by the MSPCrash Team) Section I. - Introduction: On Sunday, October 8, 2023, at approximately 2151 hours, Troopers from the Maryland State Police Forestville Barrack responded for a two vehicle crash in the area of the southbound side of Crain Highway (U.S. Route 301) south of John Hansen Highway (U.S. Route 50), Bowie, Prince Georges County, Maryland. Troopers arrived on scene and located a white Honda Civic and a multicolored Kenworth dump truck. The Honda was displaying Virginia registration, UBX2458. The Kenworth was displaying Maryland registration E63883D. The Honda was off of the right shoulder facing northbound and the Kenworth was overturned on its side on the right shoulder. Troopers located the driver of the Honda with injuries incompatible with life and the driver was pronounced decease at 2208 hours by Bowie Fire Department Chief 843B. Troopers requested a Collision Reconstruction Specialist. I, TFC Muller #6905, was notified at 2243 hours and arrived on scene at 2254 hours. Rodriguez was transported by ground to University of Maryland Capitol Regional Hospital with non-life-threatening injuries. Avilia was transported to the Office of the Chief Medical Examiner in Baltimore. During my inspection of the Honda, an empty bottle of Ciroc Peach Vodka was located on the rear passenger floorboard. It is suspected that Avila was impaired at the time of the crash however, results are pending analysis from the OCME. The following report documents my activities as part of the investigation. The scope of this investigation will address the various elements that caused and/or contributed to the collision event. The scope of this investigation was accomplished by direct and indirect action. Section II. - Scene Description: (The following descriptions are based on the area where the collision occurred.) Primary Roadway: US Route 301 US Route 301 is a multi-lane highway that runs in a north/south direction. In the area of the crash, Route 301 has two southbound lanes and is separated from the northbound lanes by a grassy median with trees and shrubbery.The left shoulder was separated from lane number 1 by a solid yellow lane line. Approximately 1.5 feet to the left of the solid yellow lane line were Sonic Nap Alert Pattern (SNAP) strips that ran parallel to the solid yellow lane line. SNAP strips are more commonly referred to as rumble strips. SNAP strips are devices that have been put into place so that when a vehicles tire roll over the strip, they produce a distinct warning sound and vibration to alert motorists. Lane number 1 was separated from lane number 2 by a broken white lane line. Lane number 2 was separated from the right shoulder by a solid white lane line. The roadway was constructed of pressed asphalt material which appeared to be in good condition with no collision-related defects. The roadway was a slight downhill grade. There were no fixed view obstructions that could have contributed to the collision. The road surface was dry. The posted speed limit was 50 miles-per-hour. There was roadway lighting under the overpass and in the area of the collision. It was noted that the lights were operating during the investigation. Environmental Conditions: High/Low Temperature: 62 Degrees / 49 Degrees Precipitation: 0.10 inches of rain Wind: 10 MPH wind coming out of the west Sun Rise/Set: 0710 hours / 1840 hours Moon: Waning Crescent. Section III. - Scene Evidence: In the area of impact, there were gouge marks, scrape marks, and evidence of skidding post impact. The roadway evidence started under the overpass and continued until the vehicles left the roadway or overturned. The Honda traveled approximately 226 feet from the area of impact to final rest. The Kenworth traveled approximately 252 feet from the area of impact to final rest. Measurements were gathred using a measuring tape. The area of impact and suspected path of travel were marked with spray paint. Section IV. - Vehicle(s) Involved: Vehicle #1: 2018 White Honda Civic Virginia Registration,UBX2458 VIN:SHHFK7H26JU400228 Damage: The Honda sustained major front end damage. The engine compartment was destroyed and was pushed back into th passenger compartment. The A Pillar on the drivers side of the Honda was also damaged. The dashboard of the Honda was severely damaged as a result of the engine compartment being forced back into the passenger compartment. There was airbag deployment throughout the vehicle. Vehicle #2: 1987 Kenworth T8 Series Dump truck. Maryland Registration,E63883D VIN:2NKDLA9X4HM345429 Damage: The vehicle was on its passenger side and had sustained damage on all sides from the crash. The vehicle had lost its load and spilled the hot asphalt on the grassy shoulder. See the Department of Transportation Post-Crash Inspection Report completed by S/Tpr Rust for further detail on the damages. Section V. - Person(s) Involved: Person #1: (Deceased) Jeffery Anthony Avila Lopez Hispanic Male DOB: 06/21/1999 13413 Bryce Ct Herndon,Virginia 20170 Valid Class D Drivers License in Virginia Person #2: (Injured) Santos O Rodriguez Bermudez Hispanic Male DOB: 04/10/1983 8105 Holiday Ave Fort Washington, Maryland 20744 Valid Class C Drivers License in Maryland. Eligible for a Commercial Drivers License. Section VI. - Crash Dynamics: Through my investigation the following sequence of events have been determined. The Kenworth was being operated by Santos O Rodriguez Bermudez, Hispanic Male, 04/10/1983, in the number two lane of southbound Route 301 underneath the overpass for Route 50. The Honda was being operated by Jeffery Anthony Avila Lopez, Hispanic Male, 06/21/1999, behind the Kenworth in lane number two. Avila was suspected to be traveling above the posted speed limit when he struck the rear of the Kenworth. The impact of the crash caused the Honda to go underneath the Kenworth causing fatal injuries to Avila. The Honda then traveled to its uncontrolled final rest off of the right shoulder. Post initial collision, the Kenworth then traveled to its uncontrolled final rest where it overturned and spilled its load of hot asphalt. Section VII. - Attachments that were included in for this report: The following items were attached to this report: Photographs were uploaded to VeriPic under this case number. ACRS Not to scale diagram. Conclusion: The crash was a result of Avilia traveling above the posted speed limit and failing to slow for the vehicle in front of him. Had Avilia been traveling at a slower speed, the crash could have been avoided. At this time I am waiting on toxicology to determine if alcohol was a factor and waiting on Sgt. Zarzecki to review the Event Data Recorder for the Honda. This case will remain open pending further investigation. A supplement will be completed for any additional investigation to include the autopsy report. TFC J. Muller #6905 Maryland State Police Waterloo Barrack 7777 Washington Blvd. Jessup, Maryland 20794 410-799-2101

Detailed Crash Investigation Supplement Section I. - Narrative On Sunday, October 8, 2023, at approximately 2155 hours, Troopers assigned to the Maryland State Police Forestville Barrack were dispatched to investigate a two-vehicle collision that occurred on the southbound side of Crain Highway (US 301), south of the John Hanson Highway (US 50), Bowie, Prince Georges County, Maryland. Due to the nature of the collision, the Maryland State Police Forestville Barrack made a request for a regional Crash Team investigator to respond to the collision scene to assume the investigation. Trooper First Class (TFC) Jacob Muller #6905, an Advanced Collision Investigator (ACI) assigned to the Maryland State Police Waterloo Barrack, responded as requested.Due to the nature of the collision, TFC Muller requested I, Sergeant Kevin Zarzecki #6202, assigned to the Maryland State Police Crash Team, assist with the investigation.The attached supplement report will document my activities as part of the collision investigation. As part of my assignment, I was tasked with imaging the Honda Civics Event Data Recorder (EDR) utilizing Bosch Crash Data Retrieval software. Conclusion: Upon approval, this report will be provided to TFC Muller for inclusion into his investigation. Any further investigative assistance by this investigator will be captured under a separate supplement report. Authored by: Sergeant Kevin Zarzecki #6202 Maryland Department of State Police Crash Team Forestville Office 3500 Forestville Road Forestville, Maryland 20747 301-669-8100 ext. 8124 kevin.zarzecki@maryland.gov
